<TITLE> Diageo to buy Rosenblum Cellars for $105 mln </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Jan 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Diageo, the world's biggest alcoholic drinks maker, said on Monday it had agreed to buy Californian wine maker Rosenblum Cellars for $105 million. Diageo, the group behind Smirnoff Vodka, Guinness and Johnnie Walker whisky, said it anticipated that the deal would be "profit positive" during the fourth full-year of ownership. Based in Alameda, California, Rosenblum Cellars was founded in 1978 and is one of the leading producers of rich and spicy, deep red Zinfandel and Rhone wines in the United States. It uses grapes from vineyards around California, with bottles costing between $12 to $100, according to the firm's website. It will be blended into Diageo's Chateau & Estate Wines division, part of its North American division, adding to Diageo's swathe of global wine brands such as Beaulieu Vineyard, Sterling Vineyards, Edna Valley Vineyard and Provenance Vineyards. "The acquisition of Rosenblum Cellars represents an important strategic fit for us, as it enhances Diageo's presence in the premium Zinfandel segment, one of the fastest growing varietals in the US," Ivan Menezes, Diageo's North America president, said in a statement. It is the latest move by the UK-based drinks maker to tap into growing drinks markets. It has a $7 billion pound bid on the table for Swedish state-owned Absolut Vod
